1. Determine the possible values of X: 0, 1, 2;
2. Calculate the probability of each value: 
   P(X=0)=(Number of subjects with scores not higher than 90 in the first test × Number of subjects with scores not higher than 90 in the second test)/(6×6)=(2×3)/36=1/6;
   P(X=1)=(Number of subjects with scores higher than 90 in the first test × Number of subjects with scores not higher than 90 in the second test + Number of subjects with scores not higher than 90 in the first test × Number of subjects with scores higher than 90 in the second test)/36=(4×3+2×3)/36=18/36=1/2;
   P(X=2)=(Number of subjects with scores higher than 90 in the first test × Number of subjects with scores higher than 90 in the second test)/36=(4×3)/36=1/3;
3. List the distribution column of X;
4. Calculate the mathematical expectation: E(X)=0×1/6 + 1×1/2 + 2×1/3=7/6.

